	  <title>Matrix Invertibility: Exercises</title>
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>For invertible <math>
                     <latex>(3,3)</latex>
                  </math>-matrices <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                  </math>, <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                  </math>, and <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                  </math>, indicate whether the following statements are always true. If a statement is always true, prove it. If not give a 
				<subordinate>
                     <hot>counterexample</hot>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>i.e. provide an example for which this statement is false.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </subordinate>.
			</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A} = \Mtrx{A}^2\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This identity does not hold for all <math>
                              <latex>(3,3)</latex>
                           </math>-matrices <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                           </math> and <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>This formula would be valid if, for all <math>
                        <latex>(3,3)</latex>
                     </math>-matrices <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math>, we had <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B} = \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math>. This, however, is not the case; i.e. there are matrices <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math> for which multiplication is not commutative. Therefore it makes sense to look for a counterexample.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The matrix equation <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A} = \Mtrx{A}^2\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                        </math> is not true in general. Here is a counterexample. Let</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{A} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right] \qquad \text{and} \qquad
\Mtrx{B} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
2 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
0  &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right]
							
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Then</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>
							
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right] 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
2 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
0  &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]
							
						</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>
							
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; -2 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right] 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right] 
							
						</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>
							
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; -2 \\
-1 &amp; 03 &amp; 0 \\
2 &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right] 
							
						</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>While</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>
							
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; -2 &amp; -1 \\
2 &amp; 0 &amp; -3 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right] \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
2 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right] 
							
						</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>
							
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
-1 &amp; 1 &amp; -2 \\
1 &amp; -3 &amp; -4 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right] 
							
						</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This is an example of matrices <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                        </math> where <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math> is distinct from <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore the given matrix identity is not always true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{C})^{-1} = \Mtrx{A}^{-1}\Mtrx{C}^{-1}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>This identity does not hold for all invertible matrices <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                           </math> and <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>We have the valid formula <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{C})^{-1} = \Mtrx{C}^{-1} \Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
                     </math>. Therefore the identity in question holds if multiplication of <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                     </math> commutes. This, however, is not the case.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Consider the row interchanging matrices</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{A} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right] \qquad \text{and} \qquad
\Mtrx{C} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]
							
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We know that <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}=\Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
                        </math>, and that <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{C}=\Mtrx{C}^{-1}</latex>
                        </math>. Now compute <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{C}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math> to confirm that <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{C} \neq \Mtrx{C}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{A}^{-1})^2 - (\Mtrx{A} - \Mtrx{A}^{_1})^2 = 4 \IdMtrx[3]</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This identity is always true.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Evaluate the brackets on the left, using the identities</para.body>
               </para>
					          <math.display>
						            <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{A}^{-1} = \IdMtrx[3] = \Mtrx{A}^{-1} \Mtrx{A}</latex>
					          </math.display>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We evaluate the individual brackets:</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{A}^{-1})^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2 + \Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{A}^{-1} + \Mtrx{A}^{-1}\Mtrx{A} + (\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}^{2} + 2\IdMtrx[3] + (\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A} - \Mtrx{A}^{-1})^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2 - \Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{A}^{-1} - \Mtrx{A}^{-1} \Mtrx{A} + (\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2 - 2\IdMtrx[3] + (\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>From this the proposed equation follows.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A})^{10} = \Mtrx{A} \Mtrx{B}^{10} \Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This identity is always true.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Use the observation</para.body>
               </para>
					          <math.display>
						            <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}^{-1}) (\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}^{-1}) = \Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{A}^{-1}) \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}^{-1} = \Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}^2\Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
					          </math.display>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>repeatedly.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{C} = \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                     </math>, then  <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A} = \Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Under the assumption that <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                           </math>, <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                           </math>, and <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                           </math> are invertible this conclusion is always true.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Multiply the identity <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{C} = \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                     </math> by <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{C}^{-1}</latex>
                     </math> on the right.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{B})(\Mtrx{A}^{-1} + \Mtrx{B}^{-1}) = 2\IdMtrx[3]</latex>
                     </math>, then <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}^{-1} = - \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This conclusion is always true.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Just evaluate the product <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{B})(\Mtrx{A}^{-1} + \Mtrx{B}^{-1})</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Prove the following statements.</para.body>
            </para>
         </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Suppose <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math> are invertible <math>
                        <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                     </math>-matrices satisfying <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B} = \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math>. Show that <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}^{-1}\Mtrx{B}^{-1} = \Mtrx{B}^{-1} \Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Using the general identity <math>
                           <latex>(\Mtrx{X}\Mtrx{Y})^{-1} = \Mtrx{Y}^{-1}\Mtrx{X}^{-1}</latex>
                        </math>, we compute</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{B}^{-1}\Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B})^{-1}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=	</text>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Here we use the hypothesis that multiplication of <math>
                                          <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                       </math> and <math>
                                          <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                                       </math> commutes.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Here we use the hypothesis that multiplication of <math>
                                          <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                       </math> and <math>
                                          <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                                       </math> commutes.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A})^{-1}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=	</text>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Using the formula for the inverse of a product again</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Using the formula for the inverse of a product again</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}^{-1}\Mtrx{B}^{-1}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This was to be shown.</para.body>
                  </para>
					
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>For an invertible matrix <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> prove   <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A}^T)^{-1} = (\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^T</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Use the identities</para.body>
               </para>
					          <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B})^T</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <text>=</text>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{B}^T \Mtrx{A}^T</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B})^{-1}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <text>=</text>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{B}^{-1}\Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>and compute   <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^T \Mtrx{A}^T</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We use the identities</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B})^T</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{B}^T \Mtrx{A}^T</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B})^{-1}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{B}^{-1}\Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>and compute.</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^T \Mtrx{A}^T</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^T</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\IdMtrx[n]^T</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\IdMtrx[n]</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This means that <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}^T</latex>
                        </math> is the inverse of <math>
                           <latex>(\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^T</latex>
                        </math>; in symbols</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>(\Mtrx{A}^T)^{-1} = (\Mtrx{A}^{-1})^T</latex>
					             </math.display>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>as claimed.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		
		
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Suppose <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math> are <math>
                        <latex>(n,n)</latex>
